Soft commodity traders find the going hard - Barriers to entry are daunting=20
and the big incumbents are facing months of adaptation and belt tightening,=20
says Adrienne Roberts.=20
Profit margins in soft commodities trading are wafer-thin. "The margins are=20
to be found between the wallpaper and the wall," said the head of a European=
=20
trading business.
"We are barely making a profit in cocoa, and we are one of the biggest=20
participants in the market," said an executive at a leading London futures=20
brokerage.=20
Enron, the largest natural gas and electricity trading house in the US,=20
announced recently that it is closing its London-based cocoa, sugar and=20
coffee brokerage business following an internal company review.=20
Members of the industry think the brokerage, Rudolf Wolff, was failing to=20
generate enough cash.=20
"US companies tend to be much more aggressive on the kind of returns they=20
want from each desk. I'm not surprised Enron decided to pack it in," said a=20
US trader.=20
Enron says it is continuing to look into other opportunities in the softs=20
industry.=20
Part of the problem is depressed markets, with low prices and thin volumes.=20
"Coffee is at a 30-year low, cocoa is flat at this time of year - I would sa=
y=20
it's extremely challenging unless you have critical mass," said the head of =
a=20
London softs desk. "Merchants are the source of our income. If they're=20
squeezed, they squeeze everyone."=20
Business conditions have been particularly difficult, for merchants sourcing=
=20
from Cote d'Ivoire, a major coffee producer and the world's largest cocoa=20
grower. Political upheaval and industry restructuring have reduced the=20
volumes of stock coming on to the physical market.=20
"The only answer is greater efficiency; lower costs," said a manager at a=20
leading soft commodities merchant.=20
Customers found a way of cutting their brokerage costs late last year when=20
the London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange took its=20
commodity products electronic.=20
Customers can now ask their brokers to provide them with trading screens,=20
with uncomfortable effects on brokers' execution fees.=20
A year ago, a client who wanted to buy 10 lots of coffee might telephone his=
=20
broker, get some advice, hear the latest on the weather in Brazil or politic=
s=20
in Cote d'Ivoire, and have his trade executed by the broker.=20
Now the client might connect directly to Liffe, put through his own trade=20
electronically and receive the documentation via the web. He may not speak t=
o=20
his broker at all.=20
Brokers earn a fee for providing the screens, but not as much as they would=20
from execution.=20
"Margins are under tremendous pressure in the futures business because of th=
e=20
move to electronic trading," said an executive at a London bank.=20
"You're seeing the tip of the iceberg now. If electronic trading is having=20
such a major effect on brokers in the softs market, what does it mean when=20
metals and energy go electronic?"=20
The execution and advice functions, once part of the same package, have been=
=20
separated. The question of where these clients will go for advice and what=20
they are prepared to pay for it has not yet been answered.=20
"The key to this business is volume," said Brian de Clare at ABN Amro. "Your=
=20
incremental cost is negligible - putting through 100,000 lots costs pretty=20
much the same as 500,000 lots. High volumes, in conjunction with good=20
service, will determine who's going to get the lion's share of the business=20
and who won't."=20
ABN Amro is one of the few participants in the industry that is expanding it=
s=20
softs business and recruiting.=20
Brokers think more people will begin dropping out of the market and there=20
will be consolidation among those in the industry. There are rumours that=20
Truxo, which belongs to the Neumann group, is thinking of withdrawing from=20
clearing customer business.=20
Head counts have come down since the demise of the open outcry trading pit,=20
but some businesses are looking to streamline further.=20
Commodities brokers that trade on the floor might have from four to seven=20
support staff to each trader. In the softs business "we're now starting to=20
see that people who were in the office are not needed to the same degree=20
because people have got their own screens", said one.=20
There is not much relief in sight. For smaller brokers, the barriers to entr=
y=20
are increasingly daunting. For the big incumbents there may be many months o=
f=20
adaptation and belt tightening ahead.=20
