Ten years ago Enron, the US energy giant, derived its profit purely from its=
=20
home market and from a few projects in the UK. It operated pipelines and=20
produced power.=20
Today, the Houston-based company has recreated itself as a global energy=20
merchant, selling and delivering gas and electricity, and its profits are=20
increasingly produced offshore.
Having consolidated its position in the UK, Enron is making a big push into=20
continental Europe to capture the growth potential in deregulating energy=20
markets.=20
The company moved into the energy selling business with the deregulation in=20
the US of gas in 1994 and electricity in 1996. It now has projects in more=20
than 40 countries. The change in strategy, away from owning infrastructure=20
and towards energy selling, has seen its earnings drift away from pipelines=20
in the US towards a rapidly growing wholesale gas and power business.=20
Enron does not release its revenue breakdown but it is clear from its volume=
s=20
that the wholesale unit - which involves energy trading and marketing and=20
risk management services - generates about 85 per cent of the company's=20
profits.=20
A third of the company's wholesale business comes from Europe, including the=
=20
UK, and Enron is focused on growing in France and Europe as a whole. Its=20
pipeline business in the US, once the engine of its growth, now comprises=20
four interstate natural gas pipelines and represents less than 10 per cent o=
f=20
earnings.=20
Enron uses its assets to supply customer power needs. It also has power=20
stations in the US, UK, Italy, Poland, Turkey and Spain.=20
Enron is aggressively eyeing Germany, France, the UK and the Nordic region=20
for opportunities offered by deregulation.=20
The company has seen growth quadruple in its wholesale business in Europe in=
=20
the past year alone. Enron does not reveal a geographical breakdown of its=20
revenue but its physical volumes of gas traded in Europe leapt from 2,469bn=20
btu (British thermal units) of gas a day in the first quarter of 1999 to=20
8,699bn btu in the same period a year later.=20
Growth in electricity traded was even stronger, jumping from 7,844 megawatt=20
hours in 1999 to 36,339 in the first quarter of last year. Those figures als=
o=20
include small gas and electricity volumes for Australia and Japan, which are=
=20
relatively new markets for Enron.=20
Ray Niles, an analyst for Salomon Smith Barney in New York, says that while=20
the UK was important, continental Europe was the key prize. The total gas=20
power market in the US is worth $300bn in revenue while Europe is worth=20
$250bn. Analysts will be looking to Enron's second quarter results, due on=20
July 12, after the company posted $406m in first-quarter profits, a 20 per=20
cent increase. Key areas of interest are likely to centre on its wholesale=20
business in Europe.=20
